---
import Base from "../../layouts/Base.astro";
import ProgressTimeline from "../../components/ProgressTimeline.astro";

// Project milestones — each "done" node links to its own standalone report.
const progress = [
  {
    date: "8 Jun 2026",
    phase: "Experiment 1 · Report 1",
    title: "The bias follows the attribute, not the language",
    summary:
      "First multilingual pipeline — 3,600 judgments on Qwen2.5-VL-7B across English, Chinese, Arabic, and Hindi. A flat .56 Demography average hid a 0.30 spread: the judge chases the prototype for Wealth (.77) and Power (.67) but sits at chance for Morality and Intellect — and the same ordering holds in every language.",
    href: "/research/cross-lingual-protobias/report-1",
    status: "done",
  },
  {
    date: "Planned",
    phase: "Experiment 2",
    title: "Confirm statistically, then push to low-resource",
    summary:
      "A mixed-effects logistic regression to confirm the attribute effect with item-level random effects; balanced Demography sampling to tighten the Wealth / Power intervals; an extension across the resource spectrum to test the “low-resource = worse” hypothesis directly; and a back-translation check on the Arabic / Hindi prompts.",
    status: "planned",
  },
];
---

<Base
  title="Cross-lingual ProtoBias · Xiaochuan Li"
  description="An applied multilingual/multimodal stress test of semantic grounding versus language- and culture-specific prototype shortcuts."
  showProgress={true}
>
  <article class="prose">
    <div class="text-xs uppercase tracking-wider text-[var(--color-text-dim)] font-medium mb-2">
      Extension · applied stress test
    </div>
    <h1>Cross-lingual ProtoBias</h1>
    <p class="text-[var(--color-text-muted)] italic !text-lg !mb-8">
      Semantic grounding versus prototype shortcuts under language variation.
    </p>

    <p>
      Cross-lingual ProtoBias applies the same semantic-vs-shortcut ambiguity to multilingual and
      multimodal evaluation: does an evaluator track the semantic content of an image-text pair, or
      does it lean on language- and culture-specific prototypes?
    </p>

    <p>
      This is an applied stress test of the central framework, not a separate thesis spine. If a
      model says an image matches a prompt, the causal-licensing question is familiar: is the
      judgment carried by semantic content, or by a prototype that happens to feel more typical? The
      ambiguity is structurally close to the one in
      <a href="/research/sc-certification">Stable Is Not Grounded</a>: a judgment can be stable and
      plausible while still being carried by the wrong feature.
    </p>

    <p>
      ProtoBias gives a controlled way to probe this. Each prompt is paired with two images: one is
      semantically correct but less prototypical, and the other is more prototypical but incorrect.
      For "a doctor treating a patient," for example, the semantically correct image might violate a
      stereotype, while the more typical image satisfies the stereotype but fails the prompt. The
      question is whether multimodal systems prefer semantic fit or prototype fit when those come
      apart.
    </p>

    <p>
      The cross-lingual turn makes the test sharper. We hold the image pairs fixed and translate the
      same prompts into multiple languages. If the model's preference changes across translations,
      then the evaluator is not simply reading the visual scene against a language-independent
      meaning. It may be importing language- and culture-specific expectations into what should be a
      semantic alignment decision.
    </p>

    <h2>Research questions</h2>
    <ul>
      <li>
        <strong>RQ1:</strong> Is prototypicality bias consistent across languages when the semantic
        content of the prompt is held fixed?
      </li>
      <li>
        <strong>RQ2:</strong> Are cross-lingual differences stronger in socially sensitive contexts
        such as wealth, intelligence, and profession than in neutral domains such as animals or
        objects?
      </li>
    </ul>

    <h2>Progress</h2>
    <p>
      The project advances in dated milestones. Each completed node links to its own standalone
      report; the headline so far is that the judge's prototypicality bias is concentrated on
      social-status attributes and barely moves with the prompt language.
    </p>
    <ProgressTimeline items={progress} accent="var(--accent-deep-purple)" />

    <h2>AI relation</h2>
    <p>
      The project uses multimodal large language models as evaluators of image-text alignment. The
      key object of study is not only whether a model gets an item right, but what kind of signal its
      decision appears to ride on: semantic consistency, visual typicality, or a culturally specific
      prototype activated by the prompt language.
    </p>

    <h2>Data</h2>
    <p>
      The project uses the ProtoBias dataset, with prompts translated into multiple languages while
      keeping the image pairs fixed. This makes the translation itself an intervention on the
      linguistic presentation of the same underlying semantic task.
    </p>

    <h2>Literature</h2>
    <ol>
      <li><a href="https://aclanthology.org/2025.findings-acl.585/">ACL Findings 2025 paper</a></li>
      <li><a href="https://aclanthology.org/2024.emnlp-main.474/">EMNLP 2024 paper</a></li>
      <li><a href="https://aclanthology.org/2022.gebnlp-1.9/">GeBNLP 2022 paper</a></li>
      <li><a href="https://aclanthology.org/2025.findings-emnlp.783/">EMNLP Findings 2025 paper</a></li>
      <li><a href="https://arxiv.org/abs/2601.04946">ProtoBias</a></li>
    </ol>
  </article>
</Base>
